{
  "texts": [
    "The increasing use of vernacular languages in literature allowed authors to reach a broader audience, enhancing their personal reputation (Aers 1992).",
    "The growing influence of the humanist movement emphasized the value of individual achievement and original thought (Rabil 1988).",
    "The Renaissance marked a shift toward recognizing individual authorship, influenced by the revival of classical learning and humanism (Burke 1999).",
    "Figures like Petrarch and Boccaccio began to emphasize the personal voice and creativity of the author (Witt 2000).",
    "This shift was further accelerated by the invention of the printing press, which enabled authors to disseminate their works more widely and maintain control over their intellectual output (Eisenstein 1982)."
  ]
}